article.headline: Van Horn fills in for Nowitzki; Stackhouse sizzles for 18
article.linkText: Nowitzki rests as Mavs handle lowly Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks could afford to give Dirk Nowitzki a break against the woeful Portland Trail Blazers. Jerry Stackhouse came off the bench to score 18 points, and the Mavericks soundly beat the Blazers 102-90 Thursday night for their sixth straight victory. The Mavericks swept the Blazers 4-0 for the first time in franchise history. The game didn't mean much to the Mavericks -- they can't get higher than the fourth seed in the Western Conference. So it was a good time to rest their All-Star forward's sore left shoulder. "He's been banged up all year," coach Avery Johnson said. "He never complains." Shareef-Abdur-Rahim had 19 points and 10 rebounds for the Blazers, who have lost nine of 10 games. Ruben Patterson, who had 18 points, was so discouraged afterward that he said he wasn't going to play in the team's final four games. "I'm done," he said. Nowitzki, who scored 31 points in the Mavericks' 95-90 victory over Seattle on Wednesday, leads Dallas with averages of 26.3 points and 9.9 rebounds. He said his shoulder was fine. "We're one of the deepest teams in the league. With guys like Stackhouse and [Keith] Van Horn off the bench who can score with anyone in this league -- that's a luxury to have," Nowitzki said. Van Horn had 12 points and seven rebounds. Shawn Bradley had a season-high 15 points for the Mavericks, who will watch the playoff picture unfold over the final week. Sacramento (48-30), Houston (48-31) and Denver (47-31) are all battling for the No. 5 seed. "It doesn't matter who we play. We're happy to be in the playoffs but whoever we get, we'll be fine," Dallas guard Michael Finley said. "If we take care of our business, we're in good shape. With or without Dirk, it's important to play well," Bradley said. Finley's dunk late in the first half put the Mavericks ahead 59-40 and brought the Mavericks reserves -- including a blue jean-clad Nowitzki -- to their feet. Dallas went on to lead 61-46 at the half. Abdur-Rahim's tip-in narrowed it to 64-56, but that was the closest Portland would come in the second half. With the victory, the Mavericks have 27 wins on the road, matching the franchise mark of the 2001-02 and 2002-03 seasons. Dallas has won six straight overall against Portland and three in a row at the Rose Garden. The Blazers are 3-20 since coach Maurice Cheeks was fired and Kevin Pritchard, the team's director of player personnel, was appointed on an interim basis. Rookie Travis Outlaw had 15 points for the Blazers, who were coming off a 95-89 loss at San Antonio on Tuesday. The frustration with the season's end was evident as the Portland players left the court. Rookie Sebastian Telfair, who had 13 points and seven assists, bowed his head as he filed slowly toward the locker room. "Everything has come to a boiling point and some people wanted to vent tonight," Blazers guard Damon Stoudamire said. "You are just counting down the days when you are playing in this situation. It is what it is."

Game notes
Portland F Darius Miles briefly left the court in the first half, spurring fears that he had aggravated his neck soreness, but he returned a short time later. He left the game again midway through the fourth quarter, this time rubbing his neck. After the game, he waited to speak with Pritchard. ... Blazers guard Derek Anderson missed his 10th straight game with a sore back. Center Theo Ratliff missed his 12th straight game with a sore shoulder. ... Nowitzki has missed four games this season.
